<chapter xml:id="chapter-cardinality" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Cardinality</title>

<p> In this chapter we will discuss how to measure and compare <q>sizes</q> of sets using bijections. </p>

<section xml:id="section-cardinality-finite">
<title>Finite sets</title>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Recall</title>

	<p>
	For <m> m\in\N </m> we have defined the
	<term><xref ref="definition-recur-induct-counting-set" text="title" /></term>
	<md> \natnumlt{m} = \setdef{n \in \N}{n \lt m} = \{ 0, \, 1, \, \dotsc, \, m-1\} </md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Clearly, <m> \natnumlt{m} </m> contains exactly <m> m </m> elements.
	In fact, we have <em>defined</em> the number <m> m </m> to be the set <m> \natnumlt{m} </m>.
	(See <xref ref="example-recur-induct-construct-nat-nums" />.)
	</p>

</paragraphs>

<p>
As the terminology implies,
we will use these sets to count the elements of other sets.
In particular, given a set <m> A </m>,
if we can match up the elements of <m> A </m> with the elements of <m> \natnumlt{m} </m>, one for one,
then <m> A </m> must also contain exactly <m> m </m> elements.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li xml:id="definition-cardinality-finite-set">
	<title>finite set</title>
	<idx><h>finite</h><h>set</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>finite</h></idx>
	<p> a set <m> A </m> for which there exists a bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> for some <m> m \in \N </m>, <m> m \ge 0 </m> </p>
</li></dl></p>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-is-unique">
	<title>Uniqueness of counting number</title>
	<p> For finite set <m> A </m> there exists <em>one unique</em> natural number <m> m </m> for which a bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> exists. </p>
</fact>

<remark><p>
	Suppose <m> A </m> is finite.
	While there is only one number <m> m </m> for which a bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> exists,
	there can be many such bijections, and the number of bijections increases as <m> m </m> increases.
</p></remark>

<exercise><p> Prove <xref ref="fact-cardinality-is-unique" /> in the case of non-empty <m> A </m>. </p></exercise>

<p>

<dl width="medium"><li xml:id="definition-cardinality-itself">
	<title>cardinality (of a finite set <m> A </m>)</title>
	<idx>cardinality</idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>cardinality</h></idx>
	<p> the unique natural number <m> m </m> for which a bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> exists </p>
</li></dl>

<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title><m> \card{A} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \card{A} </m></usage>
			<description> cardinality of the set <m> A </m> </description>
		</notation>
		<p> the cardinality of the finite set <m> A </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \cardop A </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \cardop A </m></usage>
			<description> alternative notation for the cardinality of the set <m> A </m> </description>
		</notation>
		<p> alternative notation for the cardinality of the finite set <m> A </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \ncardop\{\dots\} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \ncardop\{\dots\} </m></usage>
			<description> alternative notation for the cardinality of the set defined by <m> \{\dots\} </m> </description>
		</notation>
		<p> alternative notation for the cardinality of the set defined by <m> \{\dots\} </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl>

</p>

<example>

	<p>
	For <m> \Sigma = \ShortEngAlphabet </m>, we have <m> \card{\Sigma} = 26 </m>.
	Below are two example bijections <m> \funcdef{\varphi,\psi}{\natnumlt{26}}{\Sigma} </m> that verify this cardinality number.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption>
			Bijections <m> \funcdef{\varphi,\psi}{\natnumlt{26}}{\Sigma} </m>
			defined by a table of values.
		</caption>
		<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
			<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m> \sigma </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 0 </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 1 </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 2 </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 3 </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \cdots </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 24 </m></cell>
				<cell><m> 25 </m></cell>
			</row><row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m> \varphi(\sigma) </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{a} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{b} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{c} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{d} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \cdots </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{y} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{z} </m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m> \psi(\sigma) </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{a} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{z} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{b} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{y} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \cdots </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{m} </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \mathrm{n} </m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</figure>

</example>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Cardinality of an empty set</title>

	<p>
	What about an empty set?
	Clearly we should have <m> \card{\emptyset} = 0 </m>,
	but is this consistent with our definition of <xref ref="definition-cardinality-itself" text="custom">cardinality</xref>?
	By definition,
	to verify <m> \card{\emptyset} = 0 </m> we require a bijection <m> \natnumlt{0} \to \emptyset </m>,
	but
	<md> \natnumlt{0} = \setdef{n \in \N}{n \lt 0} = \emptyset </md>
	as well.
	</p>

	<p><dl width="medium"><li xml:id="definition-cardinality-empty-function">
		<title>empty function</title>
		<idx><h>empty</h><h>function</h></idx>
		<p> a function with domain <m> \emptyset </m> </p>
	</li></dl></p>

	<p>
	Do empty functions even exist?
	It is difficult to think of such a function in terms of an <term>input-output rule</term>,
	but remember that technically a function is defined by its graph.
	(See the <xref ref="definition-funcs-formal" text="custom">formal definition of <term>function</term></xref> in <xref ref="subsection-funcs-graph" />.)
	Since <m> \emptyset \cartprod X = \emptyset </m> for every set <m> X </m>,
	there exists a unique function <m> \emptyset \to X </m>,
	namely the function whose graph is <m> \emptyset </m>.
	And because of the empty nature of this graph,
	the facts required to establish <m> \card{\emptyset} = 0 </m> will be vacuously true.
	</p>

	<aside><title>Empty codomain</title><p>
		While functions with empty domain exist,
		note that it is not possible to have a function with empty codomain,
		<em>except</em> in the case that the domain is empty as well.
	</p></aside>

	<proposition xml:id="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions">
		<title>Properties of empty functions</title>

		<statement><p><ol>

			<li xml:id="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions-inj">
				For every set <m> X </m>,
				the corresponding empty function <m> \emptyset \to X </m> is injective.
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions-bij">
				The empty function <m> \emptyset \to \emptyset </m> is a bijection.
			</li>

		</ol></p></statement>

		<proof><p> You were asked to verify these statements in <xref ref="exercise-funcs-empty-functions" />. </p></proof>

	</proposition>

	<corollary>

		<statement><title>Cardinality of the empty set</title><p>
			The cardinality of the empty set is <m> 0 </m>.
		</p></statement>

		<proof><p>
			We are required to demonstrate an example of a bijection <m> \natnumlt{0} \to \emptyset </m>.
			As
			<m> \natnumlt{0} = \emptyset </m>,
			<xref ref="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions-bij" text="local">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-cardinality-empty-functions" />
			tells that the empty function
			<m> \natnumlt{0} \to \emptyset </m>
			is the required bijection.
		</p></proof>

	</corollary>

</paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-cardinality-properties-finite-card">
<title>Properties of finite sets and their cardinality</title>

<subsection>
<title>Finite sets versus finite sequences</title>

<p>
Recall that a function <m> \funcdef{f}{\natnumlt{n}}{A} </m> defines a
<term><xref ref="definition-recur-induct-finite-seq" text="custom">finite sequence</xref></term>
of elements from the set <m> A </m>, by setting
<md><mrow>
	a_0 \amp = f(0), \amp
	a_1 \amp = f(1), \amp
	a_2 \amp = f(2), \amp
	\amp \dotsc, \amp
	a_{n-1} \amp = f(n-1)
</mrow></md>.
If <m> A </m> is finite, then there exists such a function <m> f </m> that is
<term><xref ref="definition-funcs-bijective" text="custom">bijective</xref></term>,
which leads to the following.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-finite-set-finite-sequence">
	<!-- \label{FACT::finite.set.finite.sequence} -->
	<title>Characterization of finiteness using sequences</title>
	<p> A set <m> A </m> is finite if and only if there exists a finite sequence from <m> A </m> in which each element of <m> A </m> appears <em>exactly</em> once. </p>
</fact>

<remark><p><ol>

	<li>
		The above fact makes an important connection between functions and counting.
		If <m> A </m> is a finite set,
		<m> \funcdef{f}{\natnumlt{n}}{A} </m> is a corresponding bijection,
		and we create sequence <m> \{a_k\}_{k=0}^m </m> with <m> a_k = f(k) </m> as above,
		then we are able to list the elements of <m> A </m> in sequence:
		<md> A = \{a_0, a_1, \dotsc, a_{n-1} \} </md>.
		In turn, writing the elements of <m> A </m> in sequence is really just a way of <em>counting</em> them,
		in a manner that is roughly equivalent to counting on your fingers (if you had a lot of fingers).
		In fact, counting the elements of <m> A </m> <term>totally orders</term> the elements of <m> A </m>
		<!-- TODO XREF -->
		(a concept we will meet in a future chapter).
		<!-- \begin{inlinenote}[See]page \pageref{DEFN::total.order}, Example \ref{EXAMPLE::countable.set.can.be.totally.ordered}, in particular.\end{inlinenote} -->
		In <xref ref="chapter-countable" />, we will adapt this connection between functions and counting to determine whether it is possible to <q>count</q> infinite sets.
	</li>

	<li>
		We should note, however, that the above fact is essentially trivial once we <q>unravel</q> the definitions of
		<term><xref ref="definition-cardinality-finite-set" text="title" /></term> and
		<term><xref ref="definition-recur-induct-finite-seq" text="custom">finite sequence</xref></term>,
		as both involve a function with domain <m> \natnumlt{m} </m> for some <m> m </m> and codomain <m> A </m>.
	</li>

</ol></p></remark>

<corollary>

	<statement><p>
		A set <m> A </m> is finite if and only if
		there exists a finite sequence from <m> A </m> which contains each element of <m> A </m> <em>at least</em> once.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		If we have a sequence that contains each element of <m> A </m> at least once, we could turn it into a sequence that contains each element of <m> A </m> <em>exactly</em> once by removing repeated terms.
	</p></proof>

</corollary>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Finite sets versus bijections, subsets, and unions</title>

<p>
Bijections compose to create bijections
(see <xref ref="exercise-funcs-props-of-composition" />).
This fact lets us relate finite sets to each other.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-vs-bijection">
	<title>Bijection implies same cardinality</title>

	<statement><p>
		If one of <m> A,B </m> is finite and there exists a bijection <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m>,
		then <em>both</em> are finite and <m> \card{A} = \card{B} </m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>

		<p>
		Reconsider <q>one of <m> A,B </m> finite</q> as a disjunction:
		<q><m> A </m> is finite or <m> B </m> is finite</q>.
		Then break into cases.
		</p>

		<case>
			<title>Assume <m> A </m> is finite</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m> \card{A} = n </m>, so that there exists a bijection <m> \funcdef{g}{\natnumlt{n}}{A} </m>.
			Then <m> \funcdef{f\circ g}{\natnumlt{n}}{B} </m> is also a bijection, so <m> \card{B} = n </m>.
			</p>
		</case>

		<case>
			<title>Assume <m> B </m> is finite</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m> \card{B} = n </m>.
			Repeat the argument from the previous case,
			swapping roles of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> and using the bijection <m> \funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A} </m> in place of <m> f </m>.
			</p>
		</case>

	</proof>

</fact>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite">
	<title>Subset of finite is finite</title>

	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> B </m> is a finite set.
		<ol>

			<li xml:id="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite-subset">
				Every subset <m> A \subseteq B </m> is finite, with <m> \card{A} \le \card{B} </m>.
			</li>

			<li xml:id="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite-inj-image">
				If <m> \funcdef{f}{C}{B} </m> is an injection, then <m> C </m> is finite with <m> \card{C} \le \card{B} </m>.
			</li>

		</ol>
	</p></statement>

	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p><ol>

		<li> This is left to you as <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-finite-subset" />. </li>

		<li>
			Let <m> A </m> represent the image <m> f(C) </m>.
			Then <m> A \subseteq B </m>, so we can apply
			<xref ref="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite-subset" text="local">Statement</xref>
			and <xref ref="fact-cardinality-vs-bijection" />.
		</li>

	</ol></p></proof>

</fact>

<p> We may also relate cardinality of finite sets to the union operation. </p>

<fact>
	<title>Cardinality of unions</title>

	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are finite subsets of a universal set <m> U </m>.
		<ol>
			<li> If <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are disjoint, then <m> \card{A \sqcup B} = \card{A} + \card{B} </m>. </li>
			<li> <m> \card{A \cup B} = \card{A} + \card{B} - \card{A \cap B} </m>. </li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>

	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		The idea behind these formulas should be obvious once you draw appropriate Venn diagrams, but formal proofs are left to you in <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-union" />.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Cardinality of power sets of finite sets</title>

<problem xml:id="wexample-cardinality-pow-set"> <!-- worked example -->

	<statement><p> What is the cardinality of <m> \powset{\{1,2,3,\dotsc,k\}} </m>? </p></statement>

	<solution><p>
		We can solve this using recursion!
		In <xref ref="example-recur-induct-sequence-of-sets" />,
		we defined the following sequence of subsets of <m> \N </m>,
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow>
				A_0 = \emptyset, \quad
				A_1 = \{1\}, \quad
				A_2 = \{1,2\}, \quad
				A_3 = \{1,2,3\},
			</mrow><mrow>
				\dotsc, \quad
				A_k = \{1, 2, \dotsc, k \}, \quad
				\dotsc
			</mrow>
		</md>,
		recursively.
		We can also express the sequence
		<m> N_k = \card{\powset{A_k}} </m> recursively.
		First, <m> N_0 = 1 </m>.
		Then, since
		<md> A_{k-1} = \{ 1, 2, \dotsc, k-1 \} \subsetneqq \{1,2,\dotsc,k-1,k\} = A_k, </md>
		we can consider <m> \powset{A_{k-1}} \subseteq \powset{A_k} </m>.
		(See <xref ref="exercise-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops-subset" />.)
		In doing so, we can break <m> \powset{A_k} </m> into the disjoint union
		<md> \powset{A_k} = \powset{A_{k-1}} \sqcup \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}}. </md>
		Notice that the elements of <m> \powset{A_{k-1}} </m> are precisely those subsets of <m> A_k </m> that <em>do not</em> contain the element <m> k </m>, and therefore the elements of <m> \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}} </m>  are precisely those subsets of <m> A_k </m> that <em>do</em> contain the element <m> k </m>.
		So
		<md> B \in \powset{A_{k-1}} \quad \lgcimplies \quad B \cup \{k\} \in \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}} </md>.
		This correspondence actually gives us a bijection
		<md>
			<mrow> \powset{A_{k-1}} \amp \to \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}}, </mrow>
			<mrow> B \amp \mapsto B \cup \{k\}. </mrow>
		</md>
		(Check!)
		</p><p>
		Now we have
		<md> N_{k-1} = \card{\powset{A_{k-1}}} = \card{\cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}}} </md>.
		Since
		<md> \powset{A_k} = \powset{A_{k-1}} \sqcup \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}} </md>,
		we then have
		<md> N_k = N_{k-1} + N_{k-1} = 2 N_{k-1} </md>,
		a recursively defined sequence.
		Solving this recurrence relation by iteration yields
		<md> N_k = 2^k </md>.
	</p></solution>

</problem>

<exercise><p>
	Verify that the map
	<md>
		<mrow> \powset{A_{k-1}} \amp \to \cmplmnt{\powset{A_{k-1}}}, </mrow>
		<mrow> B \amp \mapsto B \cup \{k\}. </mrow>
	</md>
	in the solution to the preceding Worked Example is a bijection.
</p></exercise>

<p> We can use the idea of <xref ref="wexample-cardinality-pow-set" /> to prove a similar but more general fact. </p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-cardinality-power-set">
	<title>Cardinality of a power set</title>

	<statement><p> If <m> \card{A} = n </m>, then <m> \card{\powset{A}} = 2^n </m>. </p></statement>

	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		Since <m> A </m> has the same cardinality as the set <m> \{1,2,3,\dots,n\} </m>, there exists a bijection between the two sets.
		In <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-same-card-induces-same-power-set-card" />,
		you are asked to prove that two sets of the same cardinality also have power sets of the same cardinality.
		Using this fact and the result of <xref ref="wexample-cardinality-pow-set" />,
		we have <md> \card{\powset{A}} = \card{\powset{\{1,2,3,\dots,n\}}} = 2^n </md>.
	</p></proof>

</theorem>

<!-- OLD proof by induction
     TODO do I ask them to do a proof by induction in the exercises?
