</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Infinite sets</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>infinite set</title>
		<idx>infinite set</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>infinite</h></idx>
		<p> a set that is not finite </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \card{A} = \infty </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \card{A} = \infty </m></usage>
			<description> set <m> A </m> is infinite </description>
		</notation>
		<p> set <m> A </m> is infinite </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \card{A} \lt \infty </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \card{A} \lt \infty </m></usage>
			<description> set <m> A </m> is finite </description>
		</notation>
		<p> set <m> A </m> is finite </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p>
To demonstrate that a set <m> A </m> is infinite using the technical definition,
we must demonstrate that no bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> can exist,
for every cardinality value <m> m </m>.
But if <m> A </m> <em>is</em> infinite, there will be many <em>injective</em> functions <m> \natnumlt{m} \ifuncto A </m> for each <m> m </m>.
Therefore, one must demonstrate that no <em>surjection</em> <m> \natnumlt{m} \sfuncto A </m> can exist, for every <m> m </m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-cardinality-infinite-from-defn">
	<title>Demonstrating that a set is infinite from the definition</title>

	<p>
	Suppose we have an alphabet consisting of a single letter <m> \Sigma = \{\mathrm{x}\} </m>.
	Then the set of words
	<md> \words{\Sigma} = \{x,\, xx,\, xxx,\, \dotsc \} </md>
	is infinite.
	</p>

	<p>
	To verify this, we will argue that no function <m> \natnumlt{m} \to \words{\Sigma} </m> can be surjective,
	no matter the cardinality value <m> m </m>.
	So suppose <m> m \in \N </m> is fixed but arbitrary, and <m> \funcdef{f}{\natnumlt{m}}{\words{\Sigma}} </m> is an arbitrary function.
	Following the <xref ref="test-funcs-surj" text="custom">Test for Surjectivity</xref>
	(which also describes how to demonstrate that a function is <em>not</em> surjective),
	we must exhibit an example element in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> that is <em>not</em> the image under <m> f </m> of any domain element in <m> \natnumlt{m} </m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Function <m> f </m> defines a
	<xref ref="definition-recur-induct-finite-seq" text="custom">finite sequence</xref>
	of words from <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>:
	<md> w_0, w_1, w_2, \dotsc, w_{m-1}, </md>
	where each <m> w_j </m> is the image <m> f(j) </m>.
	We have two cases.
	</p>

	<case><title>Each <m> w_j </m> is the empty word</title><p>
		In this case, clearly <m> f </m> cannot be surjective since the word consisting of the single letter <m> x </m> is not in the sequence of outputs for <m> f </m>.
	</p></case>

	<case><title>Otherwise</title><p>
		In this case, consider the word we get by concatenating the words <m> w_0, w_1, \dotsc, w_{m-1} </m> together <em>twice over</em>:
		<md> w = w_0 w_1 w_2 \dotsm w_{m-1} w_0 w_1 w_2 \dotsm w_{m-1} </md>.
		(Note that this is not multiplication, we are just writing the words one after the other to create one big word.)
		Then this word is certainly longer than any of the individual words <m> w_j </m>,
		and so cannot be equal to one of those words.
		(The reason we have concatenated all the <m> w_j </m> <em>twice over</em> is so that we don't have to separately consider the case that <em>all but one</em> of the <m> w_j </m> is empty, since in that case concatenating all the <m> w_j </m> just once over wouldn't actually produce a result that is longer than that one non-empty <m> w_j </m>.)
		Since this long word is not in the sequence of image elements for <m> f </m>,
		the function <m> f </m> cannot be surjective.
	</p></case>

</example>

<remark><p>
	While we have no hope of demonstrating that a set <m> A </m> is infinite by demonstrating that functions <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> cannot be injective,
	if we wish we <em>can</em> argue using injectivity by just turning things around.
	If a bijection <m> \natnumlt{m} \to A </m> were possible, its inverse <m> A \to \natnumlt{m} </m> would also be a bijection.
	So another way to demonstrate that a set <m> A </m> is infinite is to demonstrate that no injection <m> A \to \natnumlt{m} </m> is possible, for every cardinality number <m> m </m>.
</p></remark>

<p> We can also demonstrate that a set is infinite by relating it to known infinite sets. </p>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-contains-infinite-subset">
	<title>Contains infinite subset implies infinite</title>

	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> A </m> is an infinite set.
		<ol>

			<li xml:id="fact-cardinality-contains-infinite-subset-subset">
				Every set <m> B </m> that contains <m> A </m> as a subset (<m> B \supseteq A </m>) is infinite.
			</li>

			<li> If <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m> is an injection, then <m> B </m> is also infinite. </li>

		</ol>
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p><ol>

		<li> This is left to you as <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-infinite-supset" />. </li>

		<li>
			This is just the contrapositive of
			<xref ref="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite-inj-image" text="local">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite" />.
		</li>

	</ol></p></proof>

</fact>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->

	<statement><p>
		Show that if <m> \Sigma \ne \emptyset </m>,
		then <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}} = \infty </m>, regardless of whether <m> \card{\Sigma} \lt \infty </m> or <m> \card{\Sigma} = \infty </m>.
	</p></statement>

	<solution><p>
		If <m> \Sigma \ne \emptyset </m>, then there exists some <m> x \in \Sigma </m>.
		Consider the restricted alphabet <m> \Xi = \{x\} </m>.
		In <xref ref="example-cardinality-infinite-from-defn" />,
		we demonstrated that <m> \words{\Xi} </m> was infinite.
		Clearly <m> \Xi \subseteq \Sigma </m> implies <m> \words{\Xi} \subseteq \words{\Sigma} </m>,
		so applying
		<xref ref="fact-cardinality-contains-infinite-subset-subset" text="local">Statement</xref>
		of <xref ref="fact-cardinality-contains-infinite-subset" />
		we may conclude that <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> is also infinite.
	</p></solution>

</problem>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-cardinality-rel-sizes">
<title>Relative sizes of sets</title>

<p>
We have defined a set <m> A </m> to be finite when we can count its elements by matching them bijectively with the elements of some counting set <m> \natnumlt{m} </m>.
And in this case, by defining <m> \card{A} = m </m>, we are declaring that <m> A </m> has the same <q>size</q> as <m> \natnumlt{m} </m>.
</p>

<p>
Expanding on this idea, we can think of <em>every</em> bijection as using the elements of one set to <q>count</q> the elements of another.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li xml:id="definition-cardinality-same-size">
	<title>same size</title>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>same size</h></idx>
	<idx>same size (for sets)</idx>
	<p> sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> for which there exists a bijection <m> A \to B </m> </p>
</li></dl></p>

<fact>
	<title>Symmetry of size</title>

	<statement><p> If <m> B </m> has the same size as <m> A </m>, then <m> A </m> has the same size as <m> B </m>. </p></statement>

	<proof><p> If <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m> is a bijection, then so is <m> \funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A} </m>. </p></proof>

</fact>

<fact xml:id="fact-cardinality-same-size-transitivity">
	<title>Transitivity of size</title>

	<statement><p>
		If <m> A </m> has the same size as <m> B </m> and <m> B </m> has the same size as <m> C </m>,
		then <m> A </m> has the same size as <m> C </m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p> This is left to you as <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-same-size-transitivity" />. </p></proof>

</fact>

<p> We expect our general notion of <term>same size</term> to match with just counting elements of finite sets and getting the same result. </p>

<fact>
	<title>Finite sets with equal cardinality have the same size</title>

	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are finite sets.
		Then <m> \card{A} = \card{B} </m> if and only if <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> have the same size.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>

		<case><title>Assume equal cardinality, show same size</title><p>
			Assume <m> \card{A} = \card{B} = m </m>.
			Then by definition there exist bijections <m> \funcdef{f}{\natnumlt{m}}{A} </m> and <m> \funcdef{g}{\natnumlt{m}}{B} </m>.
			Now <m> g \circ \inv{f} </m> is a bijection <m> A \to B </m>, so <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> have the same size according to the technical definition.
		</p></case>

		<case><title>Assume same size, show equal cardinality</title><p>
			Assume <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> have the same size.
			Then by definition there exists a bijection <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m>.
			Now, we have also assumed that <m> A </m> is finite,
			so there exists a bijection <m> \funcdef{g}{\natnumlt{m}}{A} </m>,
			where <m> m = \card{A} </m>.
			Then <m> \funcdef{f \circ g}{\natnumlt{m}}{B} </m> is a bijection that demonstrates <m> \card{B} = m </m> as well.
		</p></case>

	</proof>

</fact>

<warning><p>
	Your intuition may fail you when considering <q>sizes</q> of infinite sets.
	In particular, it is possible to have <m> \card{A} = \card{B} = \infty </m>,
	where <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> <em>do not</em> have the same size.
</p></warning>

<example xml:id="example-cardinality-integers-same-size-nat-nums">
	<title>Sets of integers and natural numbers have the same size</title>

	<p>
	Even though <m> \N \subsetneqq \Z </m>, <m> \N </m> and <m> \Z </m> have the <em>same size</em>!
	The following defines a bijection <m> \funcdef{f}{\N}{\Z} </m>.
	</p>

	<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="right">
		<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
			<cell><m> n </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 0 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 1 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 2 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 3 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 4 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> \cdots </m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell><m> f(n) </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 0 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> -1 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 1 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> -2 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> 2 </m></cell>
			<cell><m> \cdots </m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>

	<p>
	This bijection can be expressed by the formula
	<md>
		f(n) =
		\begin{cases}
			\frac{m}{2}, \amp m \text{ even}, \\
			-\frac{m+1}{2}, \amp m \text{ odd}.
		\end{cases}
	</md>
	</p>

</example>

<example><title>Sets of real numbers and natural numbers do not have the same size</title><p>
	In <xref ref="chapter-countable" />, we will see that even though <m> \card{\N} = \card{\R} = \infty </m>,
	the sets <m> \N </m> and <m> \R </m> <em>do not</em> have the same size!
	<!-- TODO XREF \begin{inlinenote}[See]page \pageref{THEOREM::R.uncountable}.\end{inlinenote} -->
</p></example>

<example xml:id="example-cardinality-intervals-same-size">
	<title>Intervals of real numbers of different lengths have the same size</title>

	<p>
	Recall from first-year calculus that for <m> a,b \in \R </m> with <m> a \lt b </m>,
	we define the <term>open interval</term> from <m> a </m> to <m> b </m> to be the set of all real numbers <em>strictly</em> between <m> a </m> and <m> b </m>:
	<md> (a,b) = \setdef{x \in \R}{a \lt x \lt b} </md>.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption>An interval on the real number line.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-cardinality-interval" width="67.3%">
			<shortdescription> An interval on the real number line. </shortdescription>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="cardinality.d/interval.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	It turns out that, even though they may have different <term>lengths</term>,
	the interval <m> (a,b) </m> and the unit interval <m> (0,1) </m> have the <em>same size</em>!
	(That is, they somehow contain the same <q>number</q> of numbers.)
	</p><p>
	Construct a bijection <m> (0,1)\to(a,b) </m> in two steps.
	<ol>
		<li>
			The map
			<md>
				<mrow> f \colon (0,1) \amp \to (0,b-a), </mrow>
				<mrow> x \amp \mapsto (b-a)x, </mrow>
			</md>
			is a bijection.
			(Check!)
		</li>
		<li>
			The map
			<md>
				<mrow> g \colon (0,b-a) \amp \to (a,b), </mrow>
				<mrow> x \amp \mapsto x+a, </mrow>
			</md>
			is a bijection.
			(Check!)
		</li>
	</ol>
	Then <m> \funcdef{g\circ f}{(0,1)}{(a,b)} </m> is a bijection.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption>Scaling and translating the unit interval onto another interval.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-cardinality-interval-to-interval" width="100%">
			<shortdescription> Scaling and translating the unit interval onto another interval. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO might need to make this a vertically-oriented image, stacking intervals one below the other -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="cardinality.d/interval-to-interval.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-cardinality-punctured-circle-same-size-R">
	<title>A punctured circle has the same size as <m> \R </m></title>

	<p>
	Define
	<md><mrow>
		S \amp = \setdef{(x,y) \in \R^2}{ x^2 + (y-\frac{1}{2})^2 = \frac{1}{4} } \text{,} \amp
		\hat{S} \amp = S \relcmplmnt \{(0,1)\}
	</mrow></md>.
	Here, <m> S </m> is a circle in the plane with radius <m> \frac{1}{2} </m> and centre <m> (0,\frac{1}{2}) </m>,
	and <m> \hat{S} </m> is the circle <m> S </m> <q>punctured</q> at the <q>north pole</q>.
	</p>

	<p>
	We claim that <m> \hat{S} </m> has the same size as <m> \R </m>.
	Construct a bijection <m> \hat{S}\to\R </m> in two steps.
	<ol>

		<li>

			<p>
			Let <m> X </m> represent the <m> x </m>-axis in the plane,
			so that <md> X = \setdef{(x,0)}{x \in \R} \subseteq \R^2 </md>.
			Let <m> \funcdef{f}{\hat{S}}{X} </m> be defined as follows:
			for <m> (x,y)\in \hat{S} </m>, let <m> f(x,y) </m> be the <m> x </m>-intercept of the line through points <m> (0,1),(x,y) </m>.
			</p>

			<figure>
				<caption>Projecting the punctured circle onto the real number line.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-cardinality-punctured" width="46.4%">
					<shortdescription> A diagram of a bijection projecting a punctured circle onto the real number line. </shortdescription>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="cardinality.d/punctured.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<p>
			Then <m> f </m> is a bijection.
			(Check!)
			</p>

		</li>

		<li> We also have a bijection <m> \funcdef{g}{X}{\R} </m> by <m> g(x,0) = x </m>. </li>

	</ol>
	Therefore, the composition <m> \funcdef{g\circ f}{\hat{S}}{\R} </m> is a bijection.
	</p>

</example>

<example><title>Every interval of real numbers has the same size as the entire set of real numbers</title><p>
	<xref ref="example-cardinality-intervals-same-size" /> and
	<xref ref="example-cardinality-punctured-circle-same-size-R" />
	can be combined to demonstrate that every finite-length interval <m> (a,b) </m> of real numbers has the <em>same size</em> as the entire set <m> \R </m> of real numbers.
	See <xref ref="exercise-cardinality-interval-same-size-R" />.
</p></example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-cardinality-counting-with-bijections">
<title>Counting elements of finite sets with bijections</title>

<p>
In <xref ref="chapter-counting" />,
we will begin learning how to count complicated collections by counting the <q>choices</q> needed to determine an arbitrary element in the collection.
In this section, we look at how to count collections by finding a collection of the <em>same size</em> which is easier to count.
</p>

<example><title>Counting paths with words</title>

	<p>
	Consider paths in the <m> 5 \times 10 </m> grid below that start at the bottom left and end at the top right, and only move up or right at each step.
	(One such path is drawn in.)
	How many such paths are there?
	</p>

	<image xml:id="image-cardinality-paths" width="50%">
		<shortdescription> Paths through a grid. </shortdescription>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="cardinality.d/paths.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>

	<p>
	Let <m> P </m> represent the set of all such paths.
	We can distinguish each element of <m> P </m> by the sequence of directions it takes at each step.
	Let <m> \Sigma = \{R,U\} </m>, where <m> R </m> and <m> U </m> stand for the directions <q>right</q> and <q>up</q>, respectively.
	Then for each path <m> p \in P </m> we can build a word <m> w_p \in \words{\Sigma} </m> by setting the letters of <m> w_p </m> to correspond to the steps in the path.
	For example, the path in the diagram above would correspond to the word <m> RRURUURRRRURR </m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	This assignment of words in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> to paths in <m> P </m> is a function!
	Let's call it <m> \funcdef{f}{P}{\words{\Sigma}} </m>,
	and set <m> W = f(P) </m>, the image of <m> f </m> in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>.
	This function is clearly one-to-one, as different paths must produce different words of direction indicators.
	And since every function maps its domain surjectively onto its image,
	we obtain a bijection <m> \funcdef{f}{P}{W} </m> by
	<xref ref="definition-funcs-restrict-codomain" text="title" />.
	Therefore, we can count the paths in <m> P </m> by instead counting the words in <m> W </m>!
	</p>

	<p>
	Since each path in <m> P </m> takes exactly <m> 13 </m> steps, exactly <m> 4 </m> of which must be upwards and exactly <m> 9 </m> of which must be to the right,
	we see that <m> W </m> consists precisely of those words in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> that have length <m> 13 </m> and contain exactly <m> 4 </m> <m> U </m>s and <m> 9 </m> <m> R </m>s.
	Once we learn some basic counting techniques in <xref ref="chapter-counting" />,
	you will be able to come back to this example to verify that
	<md> \card{P} = \card{W} = 715 </md>.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<xi:include href="./cardinality.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./cardinality.d/exercises.ptx" />

</chapter>
